Yes, the use of STD_LOGIC_UNSIGNED in the code for `clk_div_behav` can cause warnings when you are using the `std_logic_vector` type in your code. These warnings can appear when you are attempting to perform arithmetic operations on signals of type `std_logic_vector`. 

To avoid these warnings, it's recommended to use the `unsigned` or `signed` type from the `numeric_std` library instead of `std_logic_vector` when working with arithmetic operations. The `numeric_std` library provides better support for arithmetic operations and avoids type conversion conflicts. Here's an example of how to use the `numeric_std` library:

```
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
use IEEE.NUMERIC_STD.ALL;

entity clk_div_behav is
    Port ( clk : in  STD_LOGIC;
			count: inout unsigned(7 downto 0);
			d: inout std_logic;
           tc_out : out  STD_LOGIC;
           div_out : out  STD_LOGIC);
end clk_div_behav;

architecture Behavioral of clk_div_behav is
begin
	process(clk, tc_out, div_out)
	begin
	if clk = '1' then 
		if count = X"FF" then -- use X to specify hex values to match the previous 8bit std_logic_vector
			tc_out <= '1';
			count <= X"00";
			d <= '1';
			div_out <= d;			
		else
			tc_out <= '0';
			d <= '0';
			count <= count + 1;
			end if;
	end if;
	end process;
end Behavioral;
```

By using the `unsigned` type for `count`, we can perform arithmetic operations without causing warnings. Also, the use of `X"FF"` and `X"00"` ensures that we are using a hexadecimal equivalent instead of binary or base 10 to compare or assign values.

